You said:
Is it possible to make a searchable list via html?
ChatGPT said:

Yes, it is absolutely possible to make a searchable list using HTML, typically with the help of JavaScript. HTML provides the structure of the list, and JavaScript enables the search functionality. Here's a basic example:

✅ Basic Searchable List (HTML + JavaScript)

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Searchable List</title>
  <style>
    #myUL li {
      list-style-type: none;
      padding: 8px;
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
      margin-top: -1px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Searchable List Example</h2>
<input type="text" id="myInput" onkeyup="filterList()" placeholder="Search for names...">

<ul id="myUL">
  <li>Apple</li>
  <li>Banana</li>
  <li>Cherry</li>
  <li>Date</li>
  <li>Fig</li>
  <li>Grape</li>
  <li>Kiwi</li>
</ul>

<script>
function filterList() {
  const input = document.getElementById('myInput');
  const filter = input.value.toUpperCase();
  const ul = document.getElementById("myUL");
  const li = ul.getElementsByTagName('li');

  for (let i = 0; i < li.length; i++) {
    const txtValue = li[i].textContent || li[i].innerText;
    li[i].style.display = txtValue.toUpperCase().indexOf(filter) > -1 ? "" : "none";
  }
}
</script>

</body>
</html>

🔍 Features

  • Live Filtering: As the user types, the list updates in real time.

  • Simple to Implement: Requires no external libraries.

  • Customizable: You can style it and expand it to search tables, cards, or more complex elements.

If you'd like a version that works with larger datasets or integrates with a backend (like a MySQL database), or if you want features like sorting, pagination, or fuzzy search, I can provide that too. Just let me know the use case!

✅ Step-by-Step Guide

1. Upload the HTML file to GitHub

You can either:

  • Use the GitHub web interface to create a new repository and upload the file.

  • Or use GitHub Desktop/CLI if you're more comfortable with Git tools.

💡 Be sure to name the file exactly as provided: searchable_spec_list.html.

2. Enable GitHub Pages

Once the file is in the repo:

  • Go to your repo settings.

  • Scroll to "Pages".

  • Under "Source", select the branch (main or master) and the folder (/root or /docs).

  • Save it. GitHub will provide a URL like:

    arduino
    https://your-username.github.io/repo-name/searchable_spec_list.html

Wait 1–2 minutes for it to publish.

3. Embed the GitHub-hosted page in GoDaddy with an iframe

In your GoDaddy page HTML editor (or via code section):

html
<iframe src="https://your-username.github.io/repo-name/searchable_spec_list.html" width="100%" height="600" style="border:1px solid #ccc;"></iframe>

⚠️ Important Considerations

  • Cross-Origin Restrictions: Most modern browsers allow embedding GitHub Pages in iframes, but if you encounter a blank frame, check browser console for X-Frame-Options issues.

  • HTTPS Required: Your GoDaddy site and GitHub Pages should both be served over HTTPS to avoid mixed content warnings.

  • Mobile-Friendly: Consider adding responsive styles to adapt iframe height on mobile.

ChatGPT said:

Thanks for the screenshot — it clearly shows the unwanted outer scrollbars in the iframe. This issue usually happens when the iframe content is slightly larger than its container, often due to default margins or padding on the <body> or an undefined height.

Here’s how to fix it:

✅ Solution Options

🛠 1. Remove Scrollbars by Adjusting iframe CSS

On your GoDaddy page, adjust the iframe embed code like this:

html
<iframe 
  src="https://your-username.github.io/repo-name/searchable_spec_list_modern.html" 
  width="100%" 
  height="800" 
  style="border: none; overflow: hidden;" 
  scrolling="no">
</iframe>

🔹 scrolling="no" removes scrollbars in most browsers.
🔹 overflow: hidden makes sure the iframe doesn't allow content to overflow.

🎨 2. Ensure No Scroll-Inducing Padding in HTML File

In your HTML file (searchable_spec_list_modern.html), update the CSS to:

css
body {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0 20px 20px 20px; /* maintain horizontal padding but remove top/bottom causing overflow */
  overflow-x: hidden;
}

Also ensure your <html> tag includes:

html
<html lang="en" style="overflow-x: hidden;">

🧪 Optional: Responsive Height Adjustment (Advanced)

If your table height varies and you want the iframe to dynamically resize, you can use JavaScript + postMessage between the iframe and the parent page, but that requires access to both source and embedding environments.

This happens because:

  1. The .table-container is set to height: calc(100% - 120px)

We can use viewport units (vh) instead of percentages for reliable behavior inside iframes.

css

}

With:

css
.table-container {
  height: calc(80vh - 120px); /* Uses viewport height */
}

This way, the scrollable table always calculates based on the browser window, not the iframe parent.
